A large-scale epidemic linked to food in China could have serious repercussions, impacting events like the 2008 Beijing Olympics.
Tainted food also threatens China's food export industry, worth $27.6 billion in 2005.
The Asian Development Bank warns that tainted food affects 300 million Chinese annually, leading to potential disease outbreaks.
Efforts to improve food safety include city evaluations and emergency plans.
Calls for a unified food safety mechanism and stricter punishments for safety violations reflect public concerns.
The government aims to enhance food safety monitoring and enforcement to prevent future incidents and ensure public health.
